{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477468"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:02:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:02:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14529"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14529"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.07,0.51,0.18,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102586"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7224"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85060"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2232"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44213"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102586"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of progressive shortness of breath and dry cough. He appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. On examination, he has intercostal retractions and diffuse fine crackles on auscultation. His mother mentions that he has been losing weight over the past few months. Further history reveals that the child was adopted from overseas at six months of age, and his biological mother\u0027s medical history is unknown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates. Blood tests reveal a white cell count of 3.5 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5) with lymphopaenia. HIV testing is positive. Serum lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) is elevated at 800 U/L (100-300).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Azithromycin","Amoxicillin","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole","Ganciclovir","Fluconazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a child with symptoms and signs suggestive of Pneumocystis jiroveci pneumonia (PJP) in the context of newly diagnosed HIV infection. The progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, hypoxia, and characteristic chest X-ray findings of diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates are typical of PJP. The subacute onset over two weeks is also consistent with this diagnosis. The elevated serum LDH, while non-specific, is commonly seen in PJP and supports the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E (TMP-SMX) is the first-line treatment for PJP in both adults and children. It is typically given at high doses for 21 days. In moderate to severe cases, corticosteroids are often added to reduce inflammation and improve oxygenation. According to the referenced study by Kim et al., all 15 paediatric patients with confirmed PJP were treated with TMP-SMX, confirming its role as the standard treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad-spectrum antibiotic used for many bacterial infections. However, it is not effective against Pneumocystis jiroveci, which is a fungus, not a bacterium. While bacterial pneumonia can occur in HIV-infected children, the clinical picture here is more consistent with PJP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is a macrolide antibiotic often used for atypical pneumonias. While it can be used as PJP prophylaxis, it is not the treatment of choice for active PJP infection. It would be more appropriate if mycoplasma or chlamydophila pneumonia were suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal medication used for various fungal infections, including candidiasis, which can occur in HIV-infected patients. However, it is not effective against Pneumocystis jiroveci. Fluconazole would be more appropriate if oesophageal candidiasis were suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGanciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication primarily used for cytomegalovirus (CMV) infections. While CMV pneumonitis can occur in severely immunocompromised patients, the clinical picture and chest X-ray findings in this case are more consistent with PJP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to initiating treatment for PJP, this child will require a comprehensive evaluation of his HIV status, including CD4 count and viral load. He will need to start antiretroviral therapy once he is stabilised from the acute PJP infection. Long-term care will involve ongoing antiretroviral therapy, prophylaxis against opportunistic infections, and regular monitoring of his immune status. The study by Kim et al. emphasises the importance of early diagnosis and treatment, as delayed treatment was associated with poorer outcomes in their paediatric cohort.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumocystis jiroveci pneumonia (PJP) is an opportunistic infection that commonly affects immunocompromised children, particularly those with HIV/AIDS or undergoing chemotherapy for malignancies.","Typical symptoms of PJP include progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, and hypoxia, often with a subacute onset over days to weeks.","First-line treatment for PJP is high-dose trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, with corticosteroids added in moderate to severe cases."],"references":["Kim KR, Kim JM, Kang JM, Kim YJ. Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia in pediatric patients: an analysis of 15 confirmed consecutive cases during 14 years. Korean J Pediatr. 2016 Jun;59(6):252-5. doi: 10.3345/kjp.2016.59.6.252. Epub 2016 Jun 30. Erratum in: Korean J Pediatr. 2016 Sep;59(9):387. doi: 10.3345/kjp.2016.59.9.387. PMID: 27462353; PMCID: PMC4958702. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27462353/","Ibrahim A, Chattaraj A, Iqbal Q, Anjum A, Rehman MEU, Aijaz Z, Nasir F, Ansar S, Zangeneh TT, Iftikhar A. Pneumocystis jiroveci Pneumonia: A Review of Management in Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Non-HIV Immunocompromised Patients. Avicenna J Med. 2023 Mar 24;13(1):23-34. doi: 10.1055/s-0043-1764375. PMID: 36969352; PMCID: PMC10038753. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10038753/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85060"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14529"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85060"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-13T08:25:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T08:26:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"t